# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: threat-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] This article describes a simple and pragmatic way of doing Attack Surface Analysis and managing an application's Attack Surface.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] It is targeted to be used by developers to understand and manage application security risks as they design and change an application, as well as by application security specialists doing a security risk assessment.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The focus here is on protecting an application from external attack - it does not take into account attacks on the users or operators of the system (e.g. malware injection, social engineering attacks), and there is less focus on insider threats, although the principles remain the same.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The internal attack surface is likely to be different from the external attack surface and some users may have a lot of access.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Attack Surface Analysis is about mapping out what parts of a system need to be reviewed and tested for security vulnerabilities.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] While Attack Surface Analysis is usually done by security architects and pen testers, developers should understand and monitor the Attack Surface as they design and build and change a system.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The Attack Surface describes all of the different points where an attacker could get into a system, and where they could get data out.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] 4. the code that protects these data (including encryption and checksums, access auditing, and data integrity and operational security controls).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] You overlay this model with the different types of users - roles, privilege levels - that can access the system (whether authorized or not).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Complexity increases with the number of different types of users.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] It is important to focus on the two extremes: unauthenticated, anonymous users and highly privileged admin users (e.g. database administrators, system administrators).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Group each type of attack point into buckets based on risk (external-facing or internal-facing), purpose, implementation, design and technology.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Then, count the number of attack points of each type.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Finally, focus your review/assessment on those cases.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] With this approach, you don't need to understand every endpoint in order to understand the Attack Surface and the potential risk profile of a system.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Instead, you can count the different general type of endpoints and the number of points of each type.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] This enables you to budget what it will take to assess risk at scale, and you can tell when the risk profile of an application has significantly changed.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Microservice and Cloud Native applications are comprised of multiple smaller components, loosely coupled using APIs and independently scalable.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] When assessing the attack surface for applications of this architectural style, you should prioritize the components that are reachable from an attack source (e.g. external traffic from the Internet).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Such components may be located behind tiers of proxies, load balancers and ingress controllers, and may auto-scale without warning.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Open source tooling such as Cilium Hubble and kubeshark assist in visualizing the attack surface for Kubernetes and service-mesh deployments.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] You can start building a baseline description of the Attack Surface in a picture and notes.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Spend a few hours reviewing design and architecture documents from an attacker's perspective.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The total number of different attack points can easily add up into the thousands or more.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] You also need to identify the valuable data (e.g. confidential, sensitive, regulated) in the application, by interviewing developers and users of the system, and again by reviewing the source code.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] You can also build up a picture of the Attack Surface by scanning the application.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] For web apps you can use a tool like ZAP, Arachni, Skipfish, w3af, or one of the many commercial dynamic testing and vulnerability scanning tools or services to crawl your app and map the parts of the application that are accessible over the web.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Some web application firewalls (WAFs) may also be able to export a model of the application's entry points.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Validate and fill in your understanding of the Attack Surface by walking through some of the main use cases in the system: signing up and creating a user profile, logging in, searching for an item, placing an order, changing an order, and so on.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Follow the flow of control and data through the system, see how information is validated and where it is stored, what resources are touched and what other systems are involved.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] There is a recursive relationship between Attack Surface Analysis and Application Threat Modeling: changes to the Attack Surface should trigger threat modeling, and threat modeling helps you to understand the Attack Surface of the application.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The Attack Surface model may be rough and incomplete to start, especially if you haven't done any security work on the application before.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Fill in the holes as you dig deeper in a security analysis, or as you work more with the application and realize that your understanding of the Attack Surface has improved.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Once you have a map of the Attack Surface, identify the high risk areas.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Focus on remote entry points – interfaces with outside systems and to the Internet – and especially where the system allows anonymous, public access.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] These are often where you are most exposed to attack.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Then understand what compensating controls you have in place, operational controls like network firewalls and application firewalls, and intrusion detection or prevention systems to help protect your application.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Michael Howard at Microsoft and other researchers have developed a method for measuring the Attack Surface of an application, and to track changes to the Attack Surface over time, called the Relative Attack Surface Quotient (RSQ).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Using this method you calculate an overall attack surface score for the system, and measure this score as changes are made to the system and to how it is deployed.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Researchers at Carnegie Mellon built on this work to develop a formal way to calculate an Attack Surface Metric for large systems like SAP.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] They calculate the Attack Surface as the sum of all entry and exit points, channels (the different ways that clients or external systems connect to the system, including TCP/UDP ports, RPC endpoints, named pipes...) and untrusted data elements.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Then they apply a damage potential/effort ratio to these Attack Surface elements to identify high-risk areas.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Note that deploying multiple versions of an application, leaving features in that are no longer used just in case they may be needed in the future, or leaving old backup copies and unused code increases the Attack Surface.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Source code control and robust change management/configurations practices should be used to ensure the actual deployed Attack Surface matches the theoretical one as closely as possible.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Backups of code and data - online, and on offline media - are an important but often ignored part of a system's Attack Surface.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Protecting your data and IP by writing secure software and hardening the infrastructure will all be wasted if you hand everything over to bad actors by not protecting your backups.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Once you have a baseline understanding of the Attack Surface, you can use it to incrementally identify and manage risks going forward as you make changes to the application.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] The first web page that you create opens up the system's Attack Surface significantly and introduces all kinds of new risks.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] If you add another field to that page, or another web page like it, while technically you have made the Attack Surface bigger, you haven't increased the risk profile of the application in a meaningful way.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Each of these incremental changes is more of the same, unless you follow a new design or use a new framework.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] If you add another web page that follows the same design and using the same technology as existing web pages, it's easy to understand how much security testing and review it needs.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] If you add a new web services API or file that can be uploaded from the Internet, each of these changes have a different risk profile again - see if the change fits in an existing bucket, see if the existing controls and protections apply.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] If you're adding something that doesn't fall into an existing bucket, this means that you have to go through a more thorough risk assessment to understand what kind of security holes you may open and what protections you need to put in place.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Changes to session management, authentication and password management directly affect the Attack Surface and need to be reviewed.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] So do changes to authorization and access control logic, especially adding or changing role definitions, adding admin users or admin functions with high privileges.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Similarly for changes to the code that handles encryption and secrets.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Fundamental changes to how data validation is done.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] And major architectural changes to layering and trust relationships, or fundamental changes in technical architecture – swapping out your web server or database platform, or changing the runtime operating system.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] As you add new user types or roles or privilege levels, you do the same kind of analysis and risk assessment.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Overlay the type of access across the data and functions and look for problems and inconsistencies.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] It's important to understand the access model for the application, whether it is positive (access is deny by default) or negative (access is allow by default).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] In a positive access model, any mistakes in defining what data or functions are permitted to a new user type or role are easy to see.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] In a negative access model, you have to be much more careful to ensure that a user does not get access to data/functions that they should not be permitted to.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] This kind of threat or risk assessment can be done periodically, or as a part of design work in serial / phased / spiral / waterfall development projects, or continuously and incrementally in Agile / iterative development.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface-analysis-cheat-sheet] Normally, an application's Attack Surface will increase over time as you add more interfaces and user types and integrate with other systems.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] The **attack surface** of a software environment is the sum of the different points (for "attack vectors") where an unauthorized user (the "attacker") can try to enter data to, extract data from, or control a device or critical software in an environment.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Keeping the attack surface as small as possible is a basic security measure.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Worldwide digital change has accelerated the size, scope, and composition of an organization's attack surface.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] The size of an attack surface may fluctuate over time, adding and subtracting assets and digital systems (e.g. websites, hosts, cloud and mobile apps, etc.).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Attack surface sizes can change rapidly as well.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Digital assets eschew the physical requirements of traditional network devices, servers, data centers, and on-premise networks.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] This leads to attack surfaces changing rapidly, based on the organization's needs and the availability of digital services to accomplish it.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Attack surface scope also varies from organization to organization.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] With the rise of digital supply chains, interdependencies, and globalization, an organization's attack surface has a broader scope of concern (viz. vectors for cyberattacks).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Due to the increase in the countless potential vulnerable points each enterprise has, there has been increasing advantage for hackers and attackers as they only need to find one vulnerable point to succeed in their attack.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] One approach to improving information security is to reduce the attack surface of a system or software.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] The basic strategies of attack surface reduction include the following: reduce the amount of code running, reduce entry points available to untrusted users, and eliminate services requested by relatively few users.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] By having less code available to unauthorized actors, there tend to be fewer failures.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] By turning off unnecessary functionality, there are fewer security risks.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-surface] Although attack surface reduction helps prevent security failures, it does not mitigate the amount of damage an attacker could inflict once a vulnerability is found.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Some of the earliest descriptions of attack trees are found in papers and articles by Bruce Schneier, when he was CTO of Counterpane Internet Security.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Schneier was clearly involved in the development of attack tree concepts and was instrumental in publicizing them.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] However, the attributions in some of the early publicly available papers on attack trees also suggest the involvement of the National Security Agency in the initial development.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attack trees are very similar, if not identical, to *threat trees*.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Threat trees were developed by Jonathan Weiss of Bell Laboratories to comply with guidance in MIL STD 1785 for AT&T's work on Command and Control for federal applications, and were first described in his paper in 1982.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] This work was later discussed in 1994 by Edward Amoroso.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attack trees are multi-leveled diagrams consisting of one root, leaves, and children.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] From the bottom up, *child nodes* are conditions which must be satisfied to make the direct parent *node* true; when the *root* is satisfied, the attack is complete.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Each *node* may be satisfied only by its direct *child nodes*.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] A *node* may be the *child* of another node; in such a case, it becomes logical that multiple steps must be taken to carry out an attack.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] For example, consider classroom computers which are secured to the desks.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] To steal one, the securing cable must be cut or the lock unlocked.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] The lock may be unlocked by picking or by obtaining the key.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] The key may be obtained by threatening a key holder, bribing a keyholder, or taking it from where it is stored (e.g. under a mousemat).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Thus a four level attack tree can be drawn, of which one path is (*Bribe Keyholder*, *Obtain Key*, *Unlock Lock*, *Steal Computer*).
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] An attack described in a *node* may require one or more of many attacks described in *child nodes* to be satisfied.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Our above condition shows only *OR conditions*; however, an *AND condition* can be created, for example, by assuming an electronic alarm which must be disabled if and only if the cable will be cut.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Rather than making this task a *child node* of cutting the lock, both tasks can simply reach a summing junction.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Thus the path ((*Disable Alarm*, *Cut Cable*), *Steal Computer*) is created.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attack trees are related to the established fault tree formalism.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Fault tree methodology employs boolean expressions to gate conditions when parent nodes are satisfied by leaf nodes.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] By including a priori probabilities with each node, it is possible to perform calculate probabilities with higher nodes using Bayes Rule.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] However, in reality accurate probability estimates are either unavailable or too expensive to gather.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] With respect to computer security with active participants (i.e., attackers), the probability distribution of events are probably not independent nor uniformly distributed, hence, naive Bayesian analysis is unsuitable.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Since the Bayesian analytic techniques used in fault tree analysis cannot legitimately be applied to attack trees, analysts instead use other techniques to determine which attacks will be preferred by a particular attacker.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] These may involve comparing the attacker's capabilities (time, money, skill, equipment) with the resource requirements of the specified attack.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attacks which are near or beyond the attacker's ability to perform are less preferred than attacks that are perceived as cheap and easy.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] The degree to which an attack satisfies the adversary's objectives also affects the attacker's choices.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attacks that are both within the adversary's capabilities, and which satisfy their goals, are more likely than those that do not.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attack trees can become large and complex, especially when dealing with specific attacks.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] A full attack tree may contain hundreds or thousands of different paths all leading to completion of the attack.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Even so, these trees are very useful for determining what threats exist and how to deal with them.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Attack trees can lend themselves to defining an information assurance strategy.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] It is important to consider, however, that implementing policy to execute this strategy changes the attack tree.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] For example, computer viruses may be protected against by refusing the system administrator access to directly modify existing programs and program folders, instead requiring a package manager be used.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] This adds to the attack tree the possibility of design flaws or exploits in the package manager.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] One could observe that the most effective way to mitigate a threat on the attack tree is to mitigate it as close to the *root* as possible.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Although this is theoretically sound, it is not usually possible to simply mitigate a threat without other implications to the continued operation of the system.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] For example, the threat of viruses infecting a Windows system may be largely reduced by using a standard (non-administrator) account and NTFS instead of FAT file system so that normal users are unable to modify the operating system.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Also, users are still able to infect files to which they have write permissions, which may include files and documents.
[src:threat-modeling/attack-tree] Systems using cooperative agents that dynamically examine and identify vulnerability chains, creating attack trees, have been built since 2000.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] A **data-flow diagram** is a way of representing a flow of data through a process or a system (usually an information system).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The DFD also provides information about the outputs and inputs of each entity and the process itself.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] A data-flow diagram has no control flow — there are no decision rules and no loops.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Specific operations based on the data can be represented by a flowchart.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] There are several notations for displaying data-flow diagrams.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The notation presented above was described in 1979 by Tom DeMarco as part of structured analysis.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] For each data flow, at least one of the endpoints (source and / or destination) must exist in a process.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The refined representation of a process can be done in another data-flow diagram, which subdivides this process into sub-processes.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The data-flow diagram is a tool that is part of structured analysis, data modeling and threat modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] When using UML, the activity diagram typically takes over the role of the data-flow diagram.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] A special form of data-flow plan is a site-oriented data-flow plan.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Data-flow diagrams can be regarded as inverted Petri nets, because places in such networks correspond to the semantics of data memories.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Analogously, the semantics of transitions from Petri nets and data flows and functions from data-flow diagrams should be considered equivalent.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The DFD notation draws on graph theory, originally used in operational research to model workflow in organizations, and in computer science to model the flow of inputs and outputs across computations.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD originated from the structured analysis and design technique methodology in the middle of the 1970s.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] It was first proposed by Larry Constantine, and popularized by Edward Yourdon, Tom DeMarco, Chris Gane and Trish Sarson, who enriched the diagramming technique with different notations, data dictionary practices and guidance for the hierarchical decomposition of processes.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The primary aim of data-flow diagrams in the context of structured design was to build complex modular systems, rationalizing the interdependencies across different modules.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Data-flow diagrams (DFD) quickly became a popular way to visualize the major steps and data involved in software-system processes.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFDs were usually used to show data flow in a computer system, although they could in theory as well be applied to business process modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFDs were useful to document the major data flows or to explore a new high-level design in terms of data flow.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD consists of processes, flows, warehouses, and terminators.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] There are several ways to view these DFD components.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The process (function, transformation) is part of a system that transforms inputs to outputs.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The symbol of a process is a circle, an oval, a rectangle or a rectangle with rounded corners (according to the type of notation).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The process is named in one word, a short sentence, or a phrase that is clearly to express its essence.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Data flow (flow, dataflow) shows the transfer of information (sometimes also material) from one part of the system to another.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The flow should have a name that determines what information (or what material) is being moved.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Exceptions are flows where it is clear what information is transferred through the entities that are linked to these flows.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Material shifts are modeled in systems that are not merely informative.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Flow should only transmit one type of information (material).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The arrow shows the flow direction (it can also be bi-directional if the information to/from the entity is logically dependent—e.g. question and answer).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Flows link processes, warehouses and terminators.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The warehouse (datastore, data store, file, database) is used to store data for later use.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The symbol of the store is two horizontal lines, the other way of view is shown in the DFD Notation.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The name of the warehouse is a plural noun (e.g. orders)—it derives from the input and output streams of the warehouse.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The warehouse does not have to be just a data file but can also be, for example, a folder with documents, a filing cabinet, or a set of optical discs.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Therefore, viewing the warehouse in a DFD is independent of implementation.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The flow from the warehouse usually represents reading of the data stored in the warehouse, and the flow to the warehouse usually expresses data entry or updating (sometimes also deleting data).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The warehouse is represented by two parallel lines between which the memory name is located (it can be modeled as a UML buffer node).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The terminator is an external entity that communicates with the system and stands outside of the system.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] It can be, for example, various organizations (e.g. a bank), groups of people (e.g. customers), authorities (e.g. a tax office) or a department (e.g. a human-resources department) of the same organization, which does not belong to the model system.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The terminator may be another system with which the modeled system communicates.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Entity names should be comprehensible without further comments.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] A DFD is a graphical modeling method created by analysts often based on interviews with system users.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] It is useful for system developers, on one hand, and project contractors on the other, so the entity names should be comprehensible by modelers, users, and system analysts.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Entity names should be general (independent, e.g. specific individuals carrying out the activity), but should clearly specify the entity.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Processes should be numbered for easier mapping and referral to specific processes.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The numbering is random, however, it is necessary to maintain consistency across all DFD levels (see DFD Hierarchy).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD should be clear, as the maximum number of processes in one DFD is recommended to be from 6 to 9, minimum is 3 processes in one DFD.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The exception is the so-called contextual diagram where the only process symbolizes the model system and all terminators with which the system communicates.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD must be consistent with other models of the system—entity relationship diagram, state-transition diagram, data dictionary, and process specification models.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Each process must have its name, inputs and outputs.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Each flow should have its name (exception see Flow).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Each Data store must have input and output flow.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] Input and output flows do not have to be displayed in one DFD—but they must exist in another DFD describing the same system.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] An exception is warehouse standing outside the system (external storage) with which the system communicates.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] To make the DFD more transparent (i.e. not too many processes), multi-level DFDs can be created.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFDs that are at a higher level are less detailed (aggregate more detailed DFD at lower levels).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The contextual DFD is the highest in the hierarchy (see DFD Creation Rules).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The so-called zero level is followed by DFD 0, starting with process numbering (e.g. process 1, process 2).
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] In the next, the so-called first level—DFD 1—the numbering continues.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] For example, process 1 is divided into the first three levels of the DFD, which are numbered 1.1, 1.2, and 1.3.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The number of levels depends on the size of the model system.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD 0 processes may not have the same number of decomposition levels.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] DFD 0 contains the most important (aggregated) system functions.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The lowest level should include processes that make it possible to create a process specification for roughly one A4 page.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] If the mini-specification should be longer, it is appropriate to create an additional level for the process where it will be decomposed into multiple processes.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] For a clear overview of the entire DFD hierarchy, a vertical (cross-sectional) diagram can be created.
[src:threat-modeling/data-flow-diagram] The warehouse is displayed at the highest level where it is first used and at every lower level as well.
[src:threat-modeling/stride-security] Developed by Praerit Garg and Loren Kohnfelder at Microsoft, it provides a mnemonic for security threats in six categories.
[src:threat-modeling/stride-security] Each STRIDE category corresponds to a core principle of information security: Authenticity, Integrity, Non-repudiability, Confidentiality, Availability and Authorization.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Conceptually, most people incorporate some form of threat modeling in their daily life and don't even realize it.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Commuters use threat modeling to consider what might go wrong during the morning journey to work and to take preemptive action to avoid possible accidents.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Children engage in threat modeling when determining the best path toward an intended goal while avoiding the playground bully.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In a more formal sense, threat modeling has been used to prioritize military defensive preparations since antiquity.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Shortly after shared computing made its debut in the early 1960s, individuals began seeking ways to exploit security vulnerabilities for personal gain.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] As a result, engineers and computer scientists soon began developing threat modeling concepts for information technology systems.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Early technology-centered threat modeling methodologies were based on the concept of architectural patterns first presented by Christopher Alexander in 1977.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 1988 Robert Barnard developed and successfully applied the first profile for an IT-system attacker.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 1994, Edward Amoroso put forth the concept of a "threat tree" in his book, "Fundamentals of Computer Security Technology." The concept of a threat tree was based on decision tree diagrams.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Threat trees graphically represent how a potential threat to an IT system can be exploited.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Independently, similar work was conducted by the NSA and DARPA on a structured graphical representation of how specific attacks against IT-systems could be executed.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The resulting representation was called "attack trees." In 1998 Bruce Schneier published his analysis of cyber risks utilizing attack trees in his paper entitled "Toward a Secure System Engineering Methodology".
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The paper proved to be a seminal contribution in the evolution of threat modeling for IT-systems.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 1999, Microsoft cybersecurity professionals Loren Kohnfelder and Praerit Garg developed a model for considering attacks relevant to the Microsoft Windows development environment.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] (STRIDE is an acrostic for: Spoofing identity, Tampering with data, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, Elevation of privilege) The resultant mnemonic helps security professionals systematically determine how a potential attacker could utilize any threat included in STRIDE.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 2003, OCTAVE (Operationally Critical Threat, Asset, and Vulnerability Evaluation) method, an operations-centric threat modeling methodology, was introduced with a focus on organizational risk management.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 2004, Frank Swiderski and Window Snyder wrote "Threat Modeling," published by Microsoft Press.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In it they developed the concept of using threat models to create secure applications.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 2014, Ryan Stillions expressed the idea that cyber threats should be expressed with different semantic levels, and proposed the DML (Detection Maturity Level) model.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] An attack is an instantiation of a threat scenario which is caused by a specific attacker with a specific goal in mind and a strategy for reaching that goal.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The goal and strategy represent the highest semantic levels of the DML model.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] This is followed by the TTP (Tactics, Techniques and Procedures) which represent intermediate semantic levels.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The lowest semantic levels of the DML model are the tools used by the attacker, host and observed network artifacts such as packets and payloads, and finally atomic indicators such as IP addresses at the lowest semantic level.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Current SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) tools typically only provide indicators at the lowest semantic levels.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] There is therefore a need to develop SIEM tools that can provide threat indicators at higher semantic levels.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The threat modeling manifesto is a document published in 2020 by threat modeling authorities in order to clearly state the core values and principles that every threat modeler should know and follow.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In 2024 the same group of authors followed up the Manifesto with a Threat Modeling Capabilities document, which "...provides a catalog of capabilities to help you cultivate value from your Threat Modeling practice".
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Conceptually, a threat modeling practice flows from a methodology.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Numerous threat modeling methodologies are available for implementation.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Typically, threat modeling has been implemented using one of five approaches independently: asset-centric, attacker-centric, software-centric, value and stakeholder-centric, and hybrid.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Based on the volume of published online content, the methodologies discussed below are the most well known.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The STRIDE was created in 1999 at Microsoft as a mnemonic for developers to find 'threats to our products'.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] STRIDE can be used as a simple prompt or checklist, or in more structured approaches such as STRIDE per element.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] STRIDE, Patterns and Practices, and Asset/entry point were amongst the threat modeling approaches developed and published by Microsoft.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] References to "the" Microsoft methodology commonly mean STRIDE and Data Flow Diagrams.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis (PASTA) is a seven-step, risk-centric methodology.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] It provides a seven-step process for aligning business objectives and technical requirements, taking into account compliance issues and business analysis.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The intent of the method is to provide a dynamic threat identification, enumeration, and scoring process.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Once the threat model is completed, security subject matter experts develop a detailed analysis of the identified threats.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Finally, appropriate security controls can be enumerated.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] This methodology is intended to provide an attacker-centric view of the application and infrastructure from which defenders can develop an asset-centric mitigation strategy.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Researchers created this method to combine the positive elements of different methodologies.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] This methodology combines different methodologies, including SQUARE and the Security Cards and Personae Non Gratae.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] All IT-related threat modeling processes start with creating a visual representation of the application, infrastructure or both being analyzed.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The application or infrastructure is decomposed into various elements to aid in the analysis.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Once completed, the visual representation is used to identify and enumerate potential threats.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Further analysis of the model regarding risks associated with identified threats, prioritization of threats, and enumeration of the appropriate mitigating controls depends on the methodological basis for the threat model process being utilized.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Threat modeling approaches can focus on the system in use, attackers, or assets.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Most threat modeling approaches use data flow diagrams (DFD).
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] DFDs were developed in the 1970s as tool for system engineers to communicate, on a high level, how an application caused data to flow, be stored, and manipulated by the infrastructure upon which the application runs.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Traditionally, DFDs utilize only four unique symbols: data flows, data stores, processes, and interactors.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In the early 2000s, an additional symbol, trust boundaries, were added to improve the usefulness of DFDs for threat modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Once the application-infrastructure system is decomposed into its five elements, security experts consider each identified threat entry point against all known threat categories.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Once the potential threats are identified, mitigating security controls can be enumerated or additional analysis can be performed.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Threat modeling is being applied not only to IT but also to other areas such as vehicle, building and home automation.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] In this context, threats to security and privacy like information about the inhabitant's movement profiles, working times, and health situations are modeled as well as physical or network-based attacks.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The latter could make use of more and more available smart building features, i.e., sensors (e.g., to spy on the inhabitant) and actuators (e.g., to unlock doors).
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] Threat modeling is increasingly referenced in regulatory frameworks as a component of required risk analysis processes.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the RA-3 (Risk Assessment) control, which requires organizations to identify threats to and vulnerabilities of organizational information systems, a process that maps directly to threat modeling activities.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-model] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0 similarly incorporates threat identification and analysis within its "Identify" function.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling is an important concept for modern application developers to understand.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] The goal of this cheatsheet is to provide a concise, but actionable, reference for both those new to threat modeling and those seeking a refresher.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] The OWASP Threat Modeling project provides further information on various aspects of threat modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] In the context of application security, threat modeling is a structured, repeatable process used to gain actionable insights into the security characteristics of a particular system.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] It involves modeling a system from a security perspective, identifying applicable threats based on this model, and determining responses to these threats.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling analyzes a system from an adversarial perspective, focusing on ways in which an attacker can exploit a system.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling is ideally performed early in the SDLC, such as during the design phase.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Moreover, it is not something that is performed once and never again.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] A threat model is something that should be maintained, updated and refined alongside the system.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Ideally, threat modeling should be integrated seamlessly into a team's normal SDLC process; it should be treated as standard and necessary step in the process, not an add-on.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] These four questions will act as the foundation for the four major phases described below.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Before turning to an overview of the process, it may be worth addressing the question: why threat model?
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Why bother adding more work to the development process?
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] The following section will briefly outline some answers to these questions.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling seeks to identify potential security issues during the design phase.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] This allows security to be "built-into" a system rather than "bolted-on".
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] This is far more efficient than having to identify and resolve security flaws after a system is in production.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Proper threat modeling requires participants to think creatively and critically about the security and threat landscape of a specific application.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] It challenges individuals to "think like an attacker" and apply general security knowledge to a specific context.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling is also typically a team effort with members being encouraged to share ideas and provide feedback on others.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Overall, threat modeling can prove to be a highly educational activity that benefits participants.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling requires a deep understanding of the system being evaluated.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] To properly threat model, one must understand data flows, trust boundaries, and other characteristics of the system.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Thus improved visibility into a system and its interactions is one advantage of threat modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] There is no universally accepted industry standard for the threat modeling process, no "right" answer for every use case.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] However, despite this diversity, most approaches do include the processes of system modeling, threat identification, and risk response in some form.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Inspired by these commonalities and guided by the four key questions of threat modeling discussed above, this cheatsheet will break the threat modeling down into four basic steps: application decomposition, threat identification and ranking, mitigations, and review and validation.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] There are processes that are less aligned to this, including PASTA and OCTAVE, each of which has passionate advocates.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] The step of system modeling seeks to answer the question "what are we building"?
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Without understanding a system, one cannot truly understand what threats are most applicable to it; thus, this step provides a critical foundation for subsequent activities.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Although different techniques may be used in this first step of threat modeling, data flow diagrams (DFDs) are arguably the most common approach.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] DFDs allow one to visually model a system and its interactions with data and other entities; they are created using a small number of simple symbols.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] DFDs may be created within dedicated threat modeling tools such as OWASP's Threat Dragon or Microsoft's Threat Modeling Tool or using general purpose diagraming solutions such as draw.io.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] If you prefer an -as-code approach, OWASP's pytm can help there.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Depending on the scale and complexity of the system being modeled, multiple DFDs may be required.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] For example, one could create a DFD representing a high-level overview of the entire system along with a number of more focused DFDs which detail sub-systems.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Technical tools are not strictly necessary; whiteboarding may be sufficient in some instances, though it is preferable to have the DFDs in a form that can be easily stored, referenced, and updated as needed.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Regardless of how a DFD or comparable model is generated, it is important that the solution provides a clear view of trust boundaries, data flows, data stores, processes, and the external entities which may interact with the system.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] These often represent possible attack points and provide crucial input for the subsequent steps.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Another approach to Data Flow Diagrams (DFD) could be the brainstorming technique, which is an effective method for generating ideas and discovering the project's domain.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Applying brainstorming in this context can bring numerous benefits, such as increased team engagement, unification of knowledge and terminology, a shared understanding of the domain, and quick identification of key processes and dependencies.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] One of the main arguments for using brainstorming is its flexibility and adaptability to almost any scenario, including business logic.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Additionally, this technique is particularly useful when less technical individuals participate in the session, as it eliminates barriers related to understanding and applying the components of DFD models and their correctness.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Brainstorming engages all participants, fostering better communication and mutual understanding of issues.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Every team member has the opportunity to contribute, which increases the sense of responsibility and involvement.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] During a brainstorming session, participants can collaboratively define and agree on key terms and concepts, leading to a unified language used in the project.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] This is especially important in complex projects where different teams might have different approaches to terminology.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Due to the dynamic nature of brainstorming, the team can quickly identify key business processes and their interrelations.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Integrating the results of brainstorming with formal modeling techniques can lead to a better understanding of the domain and more effective system design.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Most modern systems are cloud-native or hybrid.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Cloud-native systems introduce unique considerations for threat modeling due to their distributed, service-oriented nature and shared responsibility model.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Cloud threat modeling frameworks such as AWS’s Well-Architected Framework – Security Pillar can serve as references.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] After the system has been modeled, it is now time to address the question of "what can go wrong?".
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] This question must be explored with the inputs from the first step in mind; that is, it should focus on identifying and ranking threats within the context of the specific system being evaluated.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] In attempting to answer this question, threat modelers have a wealth of data sources and techniques at their disposal.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] For illustration purposes, this cheatsheet will leverage STRIDE; however, in practice, other approaches may be used alongside or instead of STRIDE.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] STRIDE is a mature and popular threat modeling technique and mnemonic originally developed by Microsoft employees.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] To facilitate threat identification, STRIDE groups threats into one of six general prompts and engineers are encouraged to systematically consider how these general threats may materialize within the context of the specific system being evaluated.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] STRIDE provides valuable structure for responding to the question of "what can go wrong".
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] It is also a highly flexible approach and getting started need not be complex.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Simple techniques such as brainstorming and whiteboarding or even games may be used initially.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] STRIDE is also incorporated into popular threat modeling tools such as OWASP's Threat Dragon and Microsoft's Threat Modeling Tool.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Additionally, as a relatively high-level process, STRIDE pairs well with more tactical approaches such as kill chains or MITRE's ATT&CK (please refer to this article for an overview of how STRIDE and ATT&CK can work together).
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] After possible threats have been identified, people will frequently rank them.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] In theory, ranking should be based on the mathematical product of an identified threat's likelihood and its impact.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] A threat that is likely to occur and result in serious damage would be prioritized much higher than one that is unlikely to occur and would only have a moderate impact.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] However, these both can be challenging to calculate, and they ignore the work to fix a problem.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Some advocate for including that in a single prioritization.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Equipped with an understanding of both the system and applicable threats, it is now time to answer "what are we going to do about it"?.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Each threat identified earlier must have a response.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat responses are similar, but not identical, to risk responses.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] If one decides to mitigate a threat, mitigation strategies must be formulated and documented as requirements.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Depending on the complexity of the system, nature of threats identified, and the process used for identifying threats (STRIDE or another method), mitigation responses may be applied at either the category or individual threat level.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] In the former case, the mitigation would apply to all threats within that category.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Mitigation strategies must be actionable not hypothetical; they must be something that can actually be built into to the system being developed.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Although mitigation strategies must be tailored to the particular application, resources such as as OWASP's ASVS and MITRE's CWE list can prove valuable when formulating these responses.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Finally, it is time to answer the question "did we do a good enough job"?
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] The threat model must be reviewed by all stakeholders, not just the development or security teams.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Threat modeling can be challenging for development teams for several key reasons.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Firstly, many developers lack sufficient knowledge and experience in the field of security, which hinders their ability to effectively use methodologies and frameworks, identify, and model threats.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Without proper training and understanding of basic security principles, developers may overlook potential threats or incorrectly assess their risks.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Additionally, the threat modeling process can be complex and time-consuming.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] It requires a systematic approach and in-depth analysis, which is often difficult to reconcile with tight schedules and the pressure to deliver new functionalities.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Development teams may feel a lack of tools and resources to support them in this task, leading to frustration and discouragement.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Another challenge is the communication and collaboration between different departments within the organization.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Without effective communication between development teams, security teams, and other stakeholders, threat modeling can be incomplete or misdirected.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] In many cases, the solution lies in inviting members of the security teams to threat modeling sessions, which can significantly improve the process.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Security specialists bring essential knowledge about potential threats that is crucial for effective identification, risk analysis, and mitigation.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Their experience and understanding of the latest trends and techniques used by cybercriminals can provide key insights for learning and developing the competencies of development teams.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Such joint sessions not only enhance developers' knowledge but also build a culture of collaboration and mutual support within the organization, leading to a more comprehensive approach to security.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] To change the current situation, organizations should invest in regular IT security training for their development teams.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] These training sessions should be conducted by experts and tailored to the specific needs of the team.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Additionally, it is beneficial to implement processes and tools that simplify and automate threat modeling.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] These tools can help in identifying and assessing threats, making the process more accessible and less time-consuming.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] It is also important to promote a culture of security throughout the organization, where threat modeling is seen as an integral part of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), rather than an additional burden.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Regular review sessions and cross-team workshops can improve collaboration and communication, leading to a more effective and comprehensive approach to security.
[src:threat-modeling/threat-modeling-cheat-sheet] Through these actions, organizations can make threat modeling a less burdensome and more efficient process, bringing real benefits to the security of their systems.
